The start symbol S can only begin a derivation with one of the following pairs of non-terminals:

1. S → NT50 NT13  
2. S → NT3 NT64  
3. S → NT31 NT39  
4. S → NT24 NT20  

For the given 41-token string we need a rule whose two children together can yield 41 terminals.

• Rules (2) and (4) can produce at most two terminals, because NT64 and NT24 have only single-terminal productions and NT3 can produce at most two terminals. They cannot reach length 41.

• Rule (1) would put the single-terminal NT13 (‘t53’) at the very end of the sentence. The last token of the string is ‘t57’, not ‘t53’, so rule (1) is impossible.

• We are left with rule (3): S → NT31 NT39.  
  – NT31 can either be ‘t9’ (one terminal) or expand to NT3 NT20.  
  – In either case, the very first terminal it can emit is limited to:  
       • ‘t9’, ‘t61’, ‘t50’, or ‘t2’ (from NT0 NT24 → ‘t2 t32’) – none of which is ‘t66’.  
  – The given string begins with ‘t66’. Consequently, NT31 cannot generate the required first token, so rule (3) fails as well.

Since none of the four possibilities for S can accommodate the initial symbol ‘t66’, the grammar cannot derive the provided string.

No

The start symbol S can expand only by one of the following four binary rules:

1. S → NT50 NT13  
2. S → NT3 NT64  
3. S → NT31 NT39  
4. S → NT24 NT20  

Because the grammar is in Chomsky normal form (no re-ordering of terminals is possible), the first terminal of any derivation generated by S is produced by the left-hand child of the chosen rule.

Examine what each left-hand child can begin with:

• NT50 can eventually produce many things, but rule 1 forces the right-hand child to be NT13, which is only the terminal ‘t53’.  Hence any string derived via rule 1 must end with ‘t53’.  The given string ends with ‘t28’, so rule 1 is impossible.

• NT24 is a simple terminal rule (NT24 → ‘t32’).  Therefore, rule 4 can derive only strings whose very first token is ‘t32’.  Our string begins with ‘t38’, so rule 4 is impossible.

• NT3 can produce the terminals ‘t61’ or ‘t50’, or (by its only binary rule NT3 → NT0 NT24) a two-token sequence whose first token is either ‘t2’ or ‘t26’.  None of these possibilities matches the first token ‘t38’.  Hence rule 2 is impossible.

• NT31 is either the terminal ‘t9’ or the binary form NT31 → NT3 NT20.  As just noted, NT3 cannot start with ‘t38’, so neither alternative can yield a string whose first token is ‘t38’.  Rule 3 is therefore impossible.

Since none of the four possible first steps from S can match the required first (or last) token pattern of the given 21-token string, the string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

The start symbol S can expand in only four ways:

1. S → NT50 NT13  
2. S → NT3  NT64  
3. S → NT31 NT39  
4. S → NT24 NT20  

The first token of the given string is ‘t38’.  
Among the four possible left-hand non-terminals (NT50, NT3, NT31, NT24) only NT50 can ultimately generate ‘t38’ (via NT50 → NT21 NT10 with NT21 → ‘t38’).  
Therefore, if the string were in the language, the derivation must begin with  

 S → NT50 NT13  

NT13, however, has exactly one production rule:  

 NT13 → ‘t53’  

Consequently, the very last symbol of any string derived through this rule would have to be ‘t53’.  
The last symbol of the provided string is ‘t37’, not ‘t53’.  

Hence none of the four possible initial expansions of S can generate the given string, so the grammar cannot produce it.
